From ab2d5e2d1f7448a46498adcd275e03cd0480311b Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: dfattal <dfattal@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 14 Jul 2026 22:02:43 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 37/40] inline-3d(#625): start the frame loop when the first
 display layer registers

Every page load showed ~10-13s of horizontally smeared tiles -- photos and the
three.js scene alike, content unrecognisable -- that cleared "once you clicked
the page". The XR session's frame loop was simply never starting: an instrumented
Inline3D._frame counter sat at 0 for 30 seconds on a fresh load while
document.requestAnimationFrame ticked normally throughout.

MaybeRequestFrame() treats an inline-3d session's display layers as its valid
render state:

    if (is_inline_3d_ && !display_layers_.empty()) will_have_valid_render_state = true;

But apps request their first animation frame at session setup, BEFORE adding any
window -- our SDK does it in the Inline3D constructor -- so display_layers_ is
empty and MaybeRequestFrame correctly declines. The layers then arrive via
addImage()/addScene(), and nothing re-ran MaybeRequestFrame. The loop stayed dead
until something unrelated happened to call it: a focus blip through
UpdateVisibilityState is the usual one, which is exactly why interacting with the
page "fixed" it, and why the stall length was arbitrary.

Registering the first display layer is what makes an inline-3d session
renderable, so it must kick the loop -- the same rationale, and the same one-line
remedy, as the MaybeRequestFrame() call at the end of UpdateVisibilityState.

Why a dead loop SMEARS rather than freezing: the app repaints its canvases from
its rAF callback (the SDK does this deliberately -- see inline3d.js _frame: "a
canvas that isn't redrawn can have its layer dropped from the aggregated frame,
so the weave reads a stale sub-rect and the window flickers to a horizontal
smear"). No frames means no repaints, the canvas layers drop out of the
aggregated frame, Viz's per-target copy fails, and the batch collapses to n=1 of
6 rects -- confirmed in the service log, which showed `weave split: n=1` for 13s
before jumping to n=6 once the loop finally started.
---
 third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc | 13 +++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 13 insertions(+)

diff --git a/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc b/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc
index 2f3d77e502979..760c700a37891 100644
--- a/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc
+++ b/third_party/blink/renderer/modules/xr/xr_session.cc
@@ -2615,6 +2615,19 @@ void XRSession::OnInline3DViews(
 
 void XRSession::RegisterDisplayLayer(XRDisplayLayer* layer) {
   display_layers_.insert(layer);
+  // An inline-3d session's valid render state IS its display layers (see
+  // MaybeRequestFrame), so registering the FIRST one is what makes the session
+  // renderable — exactly like a base layer arriving. Kick the frame loop, or it
+  // never starts: apps request their first animation frame at session setup,
+  // before adding any window, and MaybeRequestFrame correctly declines then
+  // (no layers => no valid render state). Nothing re-ran it afterwards, so the
+  // loop stayed dead until something unrelated happened to call it — a focus
+  // blip via UpdateVisibilityState, say. That is the "blurred until you click
+  // the page" startup smear: with no frames the app never repaints its
+  // canvases, their layers drop out of the aggregated frame, and the weave
+  // reads stale sub-rects. Same rationale as the MaybeRequestFrame() call in
+  // UpdateVisibilityState.
+  MaybeRequestFrame();
 }
 
 void XRSession::UnregisterDisplayLayer(XRDisplayLayer* layer) {
